== Pre-Columbian == === Periods === Pre-Columbian Belizean, Mayan, and Mesoamerican history is most often divided into five periods, ie the Palaeoindian, Archaic, Preclassic, Classic, and Postclassic. These are most often defined or characterised in terms of distinguishing events or trends occurring ''within'' each period, rather than events occurring ''between'' each period (ie events separating one period from another).{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=98}} As a result, though the aforementioned sequence is well-established, and despite each period's characterisation being broadly agreed upon, various discordant upper and lower bounds have been employed for each period in scholarly literature, resulting in temporal overlaps and gaps between chronologies. Additionally, the events or trends used to characterise these periods are now known to have occurred at different times in different geographic regions, sub-regions, and settlements, rather than all-at-once across the Mayan region or Mesoamerica.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=156}} This further adds to the discordance between chronologies employed in scholarly literature, as increasingly localised upper and lower bounds for sub-regional geographic entities are used (in preference to fixed or standardised regional start and end dates).{{notetag|'Thus, [...] we should always think of [these] chronological boundaries not as fixed dates but as approximations of transitions that actually extended over many decades or even centuries (and varied from region to region)' {{harv|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=156}}.}} ==== Preceramic ==== {{main|Preceramic Period in Belize}} The Preceramic period is most often characterised as the time span ''prior to'' the first appearance of ceramics in the relevant geographic region.{{citation needed|date=July 2022}} ===== Palaeoindian ===== The Palaeoindian ie Lithic period is most often characterised as the time span ''during'' which humans first peopled the Americas.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=98}} Its ''start'' is, furthermore, commonly dated to modern humans' first arrival in the relevant geographic region.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=153}} ===== Archaic ===== The Archaic period is most often characterised as the time span ''during'' which non-nomadic farming settlements first appeared in the relevant geographic region.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|pp=98, 154}}
==== Preclassic ==== {{main|Preclassic Period in Belize}} The Preclassic ie Formative period is most often characterised as the timespan ''during'' which socioeconomically complex societies or states first appeared across the relevant geographic region.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|pp=98, 155}} It was prior thought of as the period which ''preceded'' the Classic culmination or florescence of Mayan civilisation, ie 'as a precursor to civilisation, but without the attributes of civilisation in its own right.'{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=157}} ==== Classic ==== The Classic period is most often characterised as the time span ''during'' which the social, economic, political, artistic, and intellectual development of societies or states across the relevant geographic region first peaked or culminated.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|pp=98, 155-156}} ==== Postclassic ==== The Postclassic is most often characterised as the time span ''during'' which societies or states across the relevant geographic region underwent transformation or revival.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|pp=98, 156}} It was prior thought of as the period which ''followed'' the Classic culmination or florescence of Mayan civilisation, ie 'as a decline from the Classic peak of civilisation, a time marked by decadence rather than [a Classic-like] era of continued development.'{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=157}}
Though the entire Palaeoindian-to-Postclassic time span is often characterised as ''pre-Columbian'', the Postclassic is most often end dated ''after'' 1492.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|pp=98, 153, 156}} ==== Table ==== {| class="sortable" style="text-align: left;" |+ Defining upper and lower bounds of pre-Columbian periods in 21st century literature. |- ! No ! class=unsortable style="width: 11.875%;"| Name ! class=unsortable style="width: 11.875%;"| Sub ! class=unsortable style="width: 11.875%;"| Span ! style="width: 11.875%;"| Date ! style="width: 11.875%;"| Date ! class=unsortable style="width: 11.875%;"| Event ! class=unsortable style="width: 11.875%;"| Notes |- | rowspan=3 style="vertical-align: top;"| 1 | rowspan=3 style="vertical-align: top;"| Preceramic | rowspan=3 style="vertical-align: top;"| {{unbulleted list|Palaeoindian|Archaic}} | rowspan=3 style="vertical-align: top;"| ''from'' earliest arrival of modern humans ''to'' earliest use or production of ceramics | style="vertical-align: top;"| 11785 cal BC | style="vertical-align: top;"| 11410 cal BC | style="vertical-align: top;"| Death of Naharon I | rowspan=3 style="vertical-align: top;"| cf{{hairspace}}{{notetag|Naharon I event in {{harvnb|Wrobel|Hoggarth|Marshall|2021|p=478|loc=tab. 1}}. Toledoan ie Mayahak Cab Pek event in {{harvnb|Kennett|Prufer|Culleton|George|2020|loc=tab. in supp. 1, individual AMS Lab ID PSUAMS-4290}}. Cunil ie Cahal Pech event in {{harvnb|Ebert|Pierce|Awe|2019|loc=supp. p. 6, item Lab # Beta-253771}}.}} |- | style="vertical-align: top;"| 6660 cal BC | style="vertical-align: top;"| 6570 cal BC | style="vertical-align: top;"| Death of unnamed Toledoan |- | style="vertical-align: top;"| 1375 cal BC | style="vertical-align: top;"| 1050 cal BC | style="vertical-align: top;"| Production of unnamed Cunil ceramic |- | style="vertical-align: top;"| 2 | style="vertical-align: top;"| Preclassic | style="vertical-align: top;"| {{unbulleted list|Early|Middle|Late|Terminal}} | style="vertical-ali